sols_latex:
A party trick is to use the fact that the product of eigenvalues equals
the determinant

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
\lambda_1 \lambda_2 \lambda_3 = \mathrm{det}(A)
\end{align*} and that the sum of
the eigenvalues equals the sum of the diagonal entries of \emph{A}

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
\lambda_1 + \lambda_2 + \lambda_3 = -7+3-4 = -8
\end{align*}

The determinant of \emph{A} is quickly calculated as

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
\mathrm{det}(A) = (-7)(3)(-4) + 0 + 0 - (-2)(3)(1) - 0 - 0 = 90
\end{align*}

Since $\lambda_1 = 3$ is given, we get the two equations

\begin{align*}
\lambda_2 \lambda_3 = 30, \quad \text{and} \quad \lambda_2 + \lambda_3 = -11
\end{align*}

Hence $\lambda_2 = -11 - \lambda_3$ and thus

\begin{align*}
(-11-\lambda_3)\lambda_3 &= 30 \\
\lambda_3^2 + 11\lambda_3 + 30 &= 0 \\
(\lambda_3+5)(\lambda_3+6) &= 0
\end{align*}

Hence the eigenvalues are $\lambda = 3, -5, -6$.

statement_latex:
Let \emph{A} be the $3 \times 3$ matrix given by

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
-7 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 3 & 0 \\
-2 & 0 &-4
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

It is known that $\lambda_{1} = 3$ is an eigenvalue of \emph{A}.

Find the other eigenvalues $\lambda_{2}$ and $\lambda_{3}$ of \emph{A}.
